{"title_page": "Plant based news", "text_new": "Plant Based News is a UK-based digital media outlet publishing content about veganism and plant-based living, including news and current events, health, personal transformation stories, features, and recipes.\n\nIt is known for its annual flagship documentary series (Vegan 2014, Vegan 2015 etc) which can garner in excess of 2,000,000 views.\n\n== History and profile ==\nPlant Based News was founded as a YouTube channel by Klaus Mitchell in 2014. It transitioned to a multimedia platform in 2016, when Robbie Lockie joined the organization as co-founder. The website was launched in early 2017.\n\nPlant Based News is the only vegan media outlet to have a notable YouTube presence as well as a large following across social media platforms like Instagram and Facebook, a significant readership and podcast. It reaches around 70 million people every month via its platforms.\n\n== Awards ==\nPlant Based News won The Compassionate Business Award from PETA in 2018.\nPlant Based News won an award for Best Vegan News from Viva! in 2019.<ref>{{cite web|title = Viva 25th Anniversary |url = https://www.viva.org.uk/25/awards|date = September 21, 2019}}</ref>\n", "text_old": "Plant Based News is a UK-based digital media outlet publishing content about veganism and plant-based living, including news and current events, health, personal transformation stories, features, and recipes.\n\nIt is known for its annual flagship documentary series (Vegan 2014, Vegan 2015 etc) which can garner in excess of 2,000,000 views.\n\n== History and profile ==\nPlant Based News was founded as a YouTube channel by Klaus Mitchell in 2014. It transitioned to a multimedia platform in 2016, when Robbie Lockie joined the organization as co-founder. The website was launched in early 2017.\n\nPlant Based News is the only vegan media outlet to have a notable YouTube presence as well as a large following across social media platforms like Instagram and Facebook, a significant readership and podcast. It reaches around 70 million people every month via its platforms.\n\n== Awards ==\nPlant Based News won The Compassionate Business Award from PETA in 2018.\nPlant Based News won an award for Best Vegan News from Viva! in 2019.\n", "name_user": "Jaycangel", "label": "safe", "comment": "Adding references", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Plant_based_news"}
{"title_page": "HMS Richmond (F239)", "text_new": "{{other ships|HMS Richmond}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2012}}\n{|{{Infobox ship begin}}\n{{Infobox ship image\n|Ship image=HMS Richmond with Dutch NH-90 Helicopter MOD 45155882.jpg\n|Ship caption=HMS ''Richmond'', 2013\n}}\n{{Infobox ship career\n|Hide header=\n|Ship country=[[United Kingdom|UK]]\n|Ship flag={{shipboxflag|UK|naval}}\n|Ship name=HMS ''Richmond''\n|Ship operator=[[Royal Navy]]\n|Ship ordered=December 1989\n|Ship builder=[[Swan Hunter]], [[Tyne and Wear]], United Kingdom\n|Ship yard number=\n|Ship awarded=\n|Ship laid down=16 February 1992\n|Ship launched=6 April 1993\n|Ship sponsor=Lady Hill-Norton\n|Ship christened=\n|Ship completed=\n|Ship acquired=\n|Ship commissioned=22 June 1995\n|Ship recommissioned=\n|Ship decommissioned=\n|Ship in service=\n|Ship out of service=\n|Ship renamed=\n|Ship reclassified=\n|Ship refit=LIFEX 2017-2019\n|Ship struck=\n|Ship reinstated=\n|Ship homeport=[[HMNB Devonport]], [[Plymouth]]\n|Ship identification=*{{IMO Number|8949678}}\n*{{MMSI Number|234630000}}\n*[[Maritime call sign|Callsign]]: GCOJ\n|Ship motto=*''A Deo et Rege''\n*(\"From God and the King\")\n|Ship nickname=\n|Ship honours=\n|Ship captured=\n|Ship fate=\n|Ship status={{Ship in active service}}\n|Ship notes=\n|Ship badge=[[File:HMS Richmond badge.jpg|100px]]\n}}\n{{Infobox ship characteristics\n|Hide header=\n|Header caption=\n|Ship class= Type 23 [[Frigate]]\n|Ship type=\n|Ship tonnage=\n|Ship displacement={{convert|4,900|t|abbr=on}}<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.royalnavy.mod.uk/the-equipment/ships/frigates/type-23-frigate |title=Type 23 frigate |website=Royal Navy |accessdate=4 April 2019}}</ref>\n|Ship tons burthen=\n|Ship length={{convert|133|m|ftin|abbr=on}}\n|Ship beam={{convert|16.1|m|ftin|abbr=on}}\n|Ship height=\n|Ship draught={{convert|7.3|m|ftin|abbr=on}}\n|Ship draft=\n|Ship depth=\n|Ship hold depth=\n|Ship decks=\n|Ship deck clearance=\n|Ship ramps=\n|Ship ice class=\n|Ship power=\n|Ship propulsion=\n* [[Combined diesel-electric and gas|CODLAG]]:\n*Four {{convert|1650|kW|shp}} [[MTU]] 12V4000 M53 diesel generators\n*Two [[General Electric Company plc|GEC]] [[electric motor]]s delivering 2980kW (4000 shp)\n*Two [[Rolls-Royce Spey]] SM1C delivering 23,190&nbsp;kW (31,100 shp)\n|Ship sail plan=\n|Ship speed=In excess of {{convert|28|kn|abbr=on|lk=in}} \n|Ship range={{convert|7500|nmi|km|lk=in|-3}} at {{convert|15|kn|km/h|abbr=on}}\n|Ship endurance=\n|Ship test depth=\n|Ship boats=\n|Ship capacity=\n|Ship troops=\n|Ship complement=185 (accommodation for up to 205)\n|Ship crew=\n|Ship time to activate=\n|Ship sensors=\n|Ship EW=*  UAF-1 ESM, ''or'', UAT Mod 1\n* [[Seagnat]]\n* Type 182 towed torpedo decoy\n* [[SSTD|Surface Ship Torpedo Defence]]\n|Ship armament=\n*''Anti-air missiles:''\n**1 \u00d7 32-cell [[vertical launching system|GWS.26 VLS canisters]] for 32:\n**[[Sea Ceptor]] missiles (1\u201325+&nbsp;km)\n*''Anti-ship missiles:''\n**2 \u00d7 quad [[Harpoon (missile)|Harpoon]] launchers (8x missiles)\n*''Anti-submarine torpedoes:''\n**2 \u00d7 twin 12.75{{nbsp}}in (324{{nbsp}}mm) [[Sting Ray (torpedo)|Sting Ray torpedo]] tubes\n*''Guns:''\n**1 \u00d7 [[BAE Systems|BAE]] [[4.5 inch Mark 8 naval gun|4.5{{nbsp}}inch Mk{{nbsp}}8 naval gun]]\n**2 \u00d7 [[30mm DS30M Mark 2 Automated Small Calibre Gun|30{{nbsp}}mm DS30M Mk2 guns]], ''or'', 2 \u00d7 30{{nbsp}}mm DS30B guns\n**2 \u00d7 [[Minigun]]s\n**4 \u00d7 [[FN MAG|General-purpose machine gun]]\n|Ship armour=\n|Ship aircraft=*1 \u00d7 [[AgustaWestland AW159 Wildcat|Westland Wildcat HMA2]], armed with;\n* 2 \u00d7 anti submarine torpedoes\n*''or''\n*1 \u00d7 [[AgustaWestland AW101|Westland Merlin HM2]], armed with;\n* 4 \u00d7 anti submarine torpedoes\n|Ship aircraft facilities=* Flight deck\n* Enclosed [[hangar]]\n|Ship notes=\n}}\n|}\n\n'''HMS ''Richmond''''' is a [[Type 23 frigate|Type 23]] [[frigate]] of the [[Royal Navy]]. She was launched on 6 April 1993 by Lady Hill-Norton, wife of the late [[Peter Hill-Norton, Baron Hill-Norton|Admiral of the Fleet The Lord Hill-Norton]], and was the last warship to be built by [[Swan Hunter Shipbuilders]]. She sailed from the builders on the River Tyne in November 1994. She is named for the [[Duke of Richmond|Dukedom of Richmond]].\n\n==Operational history==\n===1995\u20132000===\n[[File:HMS Richmond.jpg|thumb|left|HMS ''Richmond'' in Portsmouth Naval Base]]\n[[File:US Navy 020612-N-9407M-518 British frigate HMS Richmond (F-239) launches an AGM-84A \"Harpoon\" missile.jpg|thumb|left|''Richmond'' launching an [[Boeing Harpoon|AGM-84 Harpoon]] missile]]\n[[File:US Navy 090326-N-4774B-125 The Royal Navy frigate HMS Richmond (F 239) patrols the waters surrounding the Al Basra Oil Terminal off the coast of Iraq while merchant vessels wait to take on oil.jpg|thumb|left|''Richmond'' patrolling near the [[Al Basrah Oil Terminal|Al Basra Oil Terminal]], Iraq]]\n''Richmond'' was first deployed in 1997 to the [[Far East]] as part of the 'Ocean Wave 97' Task Group. One of the most interesting visits she made was to the [[Russia]]n port of [[Vladivostok]], an important Russian naval base, where she became the first Royal Navy vessel to visit in over 100 years. Also that year ''Richmond'' escorted the [[royal yacht]] {{ship|HMY|Britannia}} on the ship's final leg of her final tour of the United Kingdom prior to her decommissioning.\n\nIn 1998 ''Richmond'' participated in two significant [[NATO]] naval exercises and arrived in [[New York City|New York]] where she was involved in the US Navy Fleet Week. In 1999 ''Richmond'' was dispatched to the South Atlantic as part of [[Atlantic Patrol Task (South)]] and underwent a major overhaul which concluded in 2000.\n\n===2001\u20132010===\nIn 2001 ''Richmond'' joined the NATO multi-national squadron [[Standing Naval Force Mediterranean]]. In 2002 she arrived in the Caribbean where she performed tasks including obligatory \"fly-the-flag\" duties to the [[Commonwealth of Nations|Commonwealth]] countries in the region as well as undergoing trials. In June 2002, two officers were killed when ''Richmond''{{'}}s [[HMS Richmond helicopter crash|Lynx helicopter crashed]] off the coast of Virginia.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk/2046318.stm |title=Navy investigators head for crash scene |date=15 June 2002 |website=[[BBC News]] |accessdate=31 August 2014}}</ref>\n\nIn 2003, under the command of Commander [[Wayne Keble]], she deployed to the [[Persian Gulf]] on [[Armilla Patrol]] where she relieved {{HMS|Cardiff|D108|6}}.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.royal-navy.mod.uk/server/show/conWebDoc.3706/changeNav/3533 |title=News and Events |website=Royal Navy |accessdate=4 March 2008}}{{dead link|date=June 2016|bot=medic}}{{cbignore|bot=medic}}</ref> She had arrived shortly before the [[2003 Iraq War]]. When hostilities began, ''Richmond'', HM ships {{HMS|Chatham|F87|2}}, {{HMS|Marlborough|F233|2}} and {{HMAS|Anzac|FFH 150|6}} of the [[Royal Australian Navy]] provided Naval Gunfire Support (NGS) during the [[Royal Marines]]' [[2003 invasion of Iraq#Opening attack|amphibious assault of the Al Faw Peninsula]], the first amphibious assault by the Marines since the [[Falklands War]] in 1982. ''Richmond'' remained in the region at the war's end and returned home in August.\n\nIn July 2004, under the command of Commander [[Mike McCartain]], ''Richmond'' deployed on [[Atlantic Patrol Task (North)]], which encompasses the Atlantic and [[Caribbean]] regions. Two of the ports she visited early in the deployment were [[Jamaica]] and [[Belize]]. In September ''Richmond'' came to the assistance of the [[Turks and Caicos Islands]] when they were struck by [[Hurricane Frances]].  Turks and Caicos suffered only minimal damage to buildings. ''Richmond'' then sailed to [[Cura\u00e7ao]], [[Netherlands Antilles]] where she resumed her maintenance period, which had been interrupted due to the hurricane, but remained on standby to provide assistance due to the imminent arrival of [[Hurricane Ivan]].\n\nHurricane Ivan eventually hit the region, causing significant damage and fatalities, particularly inflicting enormous damage and a number of fatalities to [[Grenada]], which included immense damage to the capital [[St. George's, Grenada|St. George's]]. ''Richmond'' and her accompanying [[Royal Fleet Auxiliary]] vessel {{ship|RFA|Wave Ruler|A390|2}} came to the assistance of the island. The extent of the damage in Grenada reached such levels that [[Keith Mitchell]], Prime Minister of Grenada, was forced to relocate to ''Richmond'' after his residence was destroyed by the hurricane. The Prime Minister effectively ran his country from ''Richmond'' for several hours.\n\nHer crew having performed vital assistance on land at Grenada, ''Richmond'' steamed at her top speed for Jamaica and the Cayman Islands to assist those territories in recovering from the ravages of Hurricane Ivan.\n\n''Richmond'' returned from her deployment in December 2004, and began a refit period at [[HMNB Portsmouth|HM Naval Base Portsmouth]] in mid-2005. The refit, undertaken by [[Fleet Support Limited]], was completed in late 2006 and ''Richmond'' was returned to the operational fleet in October 2006. With 44 major upgrades to her sensor and weapon systems, ''Richmond'' was at that time one of the most capable Type 23 frigates.<ref>{{cite magazine |url=http://www.fleet-support.co.uk/Docs/FirstBase/firstbase-winter2006.pdf |title=Fresh-faced ''Richmond'' re-dedicated to the Fleet |date=December 2006 |magazine=firstBASE |page=7 |publisher=[[HMNB Portsmouth]] |access-date=3 January 2007 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070809192438/http://www.fleet-support.co.uk/Docs/FirstBase/firstbase-winter2006.pdf |archive-date=9 August 2007}}</ref> From 5 to 12 July 2010 she anchored beside {{HMS|Belfast||6}} in London to foster the ship's relations with the [[London Borough of Richmond upon Thames|Borough of Richmond-upon-Thames]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.london-se1.co.uk/news/view/4659 |title=HMS ''Richmond'' arrives in the Pool of London |date=5 July 2010 |website=London SE1 |accessdate=5 April 2019}}</ref>\n\n===2011\u2013present===\n[[File:HMS Richmond at South Quay.jpg|thumb|left|HMS ''Richmond'' moored at South Quay in London in 2017]]\nIn 2011, she deployed to the Middle East and the Asia-Pacific region, the latter for upcoming [[Five Power Defence Arrangement]] exercises, specifically Exercise Bersama Shield 11.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.navynews.co.uk/news/1215-richmond-enjoys-some-happy-torque-in-the-far-east.aspx |title=''Richmond'' enjoys some happy torque in the Far East |newspaper=[[Navy News]]}} {{dead link|date=October 2016}}</ref> She assisted with anti-piracy operations with the EU Naval Force and was also a participant in the IMEX Asia 2011.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.mod.uk/DefenceInternet/DefenceNews/MilitaryOperations/HmsRichmondDeploysOnCounterpiracyMission.htm |author=Ministry of Defence |title=HMS ''Richmond'' deploys on counter-piracy mission  |date=5 January 2011 |website=[[Gov.uk]] |accessdate=5 April 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.cornwallcommunitynews.co.uk/2011/05/10/navy-take-on-pirates-real-ones/ |title=Navy Takes On Pirates (Real Ones) |date=10 May 2011 |website=Cornwall Community News |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110513134031/http://www.cornwallcommunitynews.co.uk/2011/05/10/navy-take-on-pirates-real-ones/ |archive-date=13 May 2011}}</ref> After Singapore, she rendered honours to the fallen of [[Force Z]] (see the [[Sinking of Prince of Wales and Repulse|Sinking of ''Prince of Wales'' and ''Repulse'']]).<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.navynews.co.uk/news/1203-richmond-honours-the-dead-of-force-z.aspx |title=''Richmond'' honours the dead of Force Z |newspaper=Navy News}} {{dead link|date=October 2016}}</ref>\n\nShe took part in exercise FRUKUS 2011 with ships from the [[United States Navy]] and [[Russian Navy]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://english.ruvr.ru/2011/06/01/51118143.html |title=Russian warship heads out for joint maneuvers |date=1 June 2011 |website=[[Sputnik (news agency)|Sputnik]] |access-date=1 June 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120906022428/http://english.ruvr.ru/2011/06/01/51118143.html |archive-date=6 September 2012 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nIn early August 2013, she deployed under the command of Commander Robert G. Pedre to be the ship for the Royal Navy's Atlantic Patrol South where she carried out Maritime Security Patrols in the [[Falkland Islands]]. HMS ''Richmond'' returned to the UK in February 2014. This deployment involved high profile defence engagement visits to five continents and resulted in the ship receiving Commander British Forces South Atlantic Islands Commendation for Distinguished Service.  Of note, during her seven months away ''Richmond'' conducted visits to five British Dependent Overseas Territories including [[Ascension Island]], [[St Helena]], the Falklands, [[South Georgia and the South Sandwich Islands|South Georgia]] and [[Tristan da Cunha]]. During this deployment ''Richmond'' became the first Royal Navy warship to transit the [[Panama Canal]] in its centenary year.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.royalnavy.mod.uk/News-and-Events/Latest-News/2013/August/05/130805-HMS-Richmond-deploys |title=HMS ''Richmond'' deploys on Atlantic patrol tasking |date=5 August 2013 |website=Royal Navy |accessdate=4 April 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn October 2015 ''Richmond'' was deployed to the Mediterranean to aid the EU's fight against people smugglers due to refugees fleeing civil war in Syria. She returned to her home port on 11 December 2015.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.royalnavy.mod.uk/news-and-latest-activity/news/2015/december/11/151211-hms-richmond-home |title=Drug-busting and life-saving HMS ''Richmond'' returns home from nine-month deployment |date=11 December 2015 |website=Royal Navy |accessdate=4 April 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn October 2016 ''Richmond'' and the [[destroyer]] {{HMS|Duncan|D37|6}} were dispatched by the [[Ministry of Defence (United Kingdom)|Ministry of Defence]] to intercept and \"man-mark\" a fleet of Russian Navy vessels, including their [[flagship]] {{ship|Russian aircraft carrier|Admiral Kuznetsov||2}} passing through the English Channel on their way to [[Syria]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-37725327 |title=Russian warships pass through English Channel |date=21 October 2016 |website=BBC News |accessdate=21 October 2016}}</ref>\n\nOn 6 January 2017, ''Richmond'' featured in Series 1, episode 9 of ''[[The Grand Tour (TV series)|The Grand Tour]]''. The ship and its weaponry star in a sequence where [[James May]] and [[Jeremy Clarkson]] commandeer its 4.5 inch Mark 8 naval gun to destroy an armoured vehicle manufactured by [[Richard Hammond]].\n\nIn June 2017, ''Richmond'' docked at [[Chatham, Kent|Chatham]] on the [[River Medway|Medway]] to mark 350 years since the [[Raid on the Medway]].\n\n''Richmond'' entered refit at Devonport in the late summer of 2017, in November it was announced that on completion of the work in 2018 she will not return to Portsmouth and will switch base port to Plymouth in an effort to concentrate the Type 23s fitted with anti-submarine equipment in the city.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.royalnavy.mod.uk/news-and-latest-activity/news/2017/november/24/171124-defence-secretary-announces-type-23-base-port-moves |title=Defence Secretary announces Type 23 base port moves |website=Royal Navy |date=24 November 2017 |accessdate=28 November 2017}}</ref> The refit saw the ship become the first Type 23 to be fitted with [[MTU]] M53B diesel generators - these will be fitted to the remainder of the class (except {{HMS|Argyll|F231|2}} and {{HMS|Lancaster|F229|2}}), as well as the [[Type 26 frigate|Type 26]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.savetheroyalnavy.org/new-engines-for-the-royal-navys-type-23-frigates/ |title=New engines for the Royal Navy\u2019s Type 23 Frigates |author=<!--Not stated--> |date=27 June 2018 |website=Save the Royal Navy |publisher= |access-date= 9 April 2020|quote=}}</ref>\n\n==Affiliations==\n* [[Charles Gordon-Lennox, 10th Duke of Richmond|His Grace, The Duke of Richmond and Gordon]]\n* [[Yorkshire Regiment|The Yorkshire Regiment (14th/15th, 19th and 33rd/76th Foot)]]\n* [[Worshipful Company of Basketmakers]]\n* [[Richmond, North Yorkshire|Town of Richmond]]\n* [[London Borough of Richmond upon Thames|Richmond upon Thames]]\n* [[London Nautical School]]\n\n== See also ==\n* [[HMS Richmond helicopter crash]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category}}\n*{{cite web |url=https://www.royalnavy.mod.uk/our-organisation/the-fighting-arms/surface-fleet/frigates/type-23/hms-richmond |title=HMS ''Richmond'' |website=Royal Navy}}\n\n{{Type 23 frigate}}\n{{Royal Navy ships}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Richmond}}\n[[Category:Active frigates of the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Ships built by Swan Hunter]]\n[[Category:Ships built on the River Tyne]]\n[[Category:1993 ships]]\n[[Category:Type 23 frigates of the Royal Navy]]\n", "text_old": "{{other ships|HMS Richmond}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2012}}\n{|{{Infobox ship begin}}\n{{Infobox ship image\n|Ship image=HMS Richmond with Dutch NH-90 Helicopter MOD 45155882.jpg\n|Ship caption=HMS ''Richmond'', 2013\n}}\n{{Infobox ship career\n|Hide header=\n|Ship country=[[United Kingdom|UK]]\n|Ship flag={{shipboxflag|UK|naval}}\n|Ship name=HMS ''Richmond''\n|Ship operator=[[Royal Navy]]\n|Ship ordered=December 1989\n|Ship builder=[[Swan Hunter]], [[Tyne and Wear]], United Kingdom\n|Ship yard number=\n|Ship awarded=\n|Ship laid down=16 February 1992\n|Ship launched=6 April 1993\n|Ship sponsor=Lady Hill-Norton\n|Ship christened=\n|Ship completed=\n|Ship acquired=\n|Ship commissioned=22 June 1995\n|Ship recommissioned=\n|Ship decommissioned=\n|Ship in service=\n|Ship out of service=\n|Ship renamed=\n|Ship reclassified=\n|Ship refit=LIFEX 2017-2019\n|Ship struck=\n|Ship reinstated=\n|Ship homeport=[[HMNB Devonport]], [[Plymouth]]\n|Ship identification=*{{IMO Number|8949678}}\n*{{MMSI Number|234630000}}\n*[[Maritime call sign|Callsign]]: GCOJ\n|Ship motto=*''A Deo et Rege''\n*(\"From God and the King\")\n|Ship nickname=\n|Ship honours=\n|Ship captured=\n|Ship fate=\n|Ship status={{Ship in active service}}\n|Ship notes=\n|Ship badge=[[File:HMS Richmond badge.jpg|100px]]\n}}\n{{Infobox ship characteristics\n|Hide header=\n|Header caption=\n|Ship class= Type 23 [[Frigate]]\n|Ship type=\n|Ship tonnage=\n|Ship displacement={{convert|4,900|t|abbr=on}}<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.royalnavy.mod.uk/the-equipment/ships/frigates/type-23-frigate |title=Type 23 frigate |website=Royal Navy |accessdate=4 April 2019}}</ref>\n|Ship tons burthen=\n|Ship length={{convert|133|m|ftin|abbr=on}}\n|Ship beam={{convert|16.1|m|ftin|abbr=on}}\n|Ship height=\n|Ship draught={{convert|7.3|m|ftin|abbr=on}}\n|Ship draft=\n|Ship depth=\n|Ship hold depth=\n|Ship decks=\n|Ship deck clearance=\n|Ship ramps=\n|Ship ice class=\n|Ship power=\n|Ship propulsion=\n* [[Combined diesel-electric and gas|CODLAG]]:\n*Four 1510 kW (2,025 shp) [[Paxman Valenta]] 12CM diesel generators\n*Two [[General Electric Company plc|GEC]] [[electric motor]]s delivering 2980kW (4000 shp)\n*Two [[Rolls-Royce Spey]] SM1C delivering 23,190&nbsp;kW (31,100 shp)\n|Ship sail plan=\n|Ship speed=In excess of {{convert|28|kn|abbr=on|lk=in}} \n|Ship range={{convert|7500|nmi|km|lk=in|-3}} at {{convert|15|kn|km/h|abbr=on}}\n|Ship endurance=\n|Ship test depth=\n|Ship boats=\n|Ship capacity=\n|Ship troops=\n|Ship complement=185 (accommodation for up to 205)\n|Ship crew=\n|Ship time to activate=\n|Ship sensors=\n|Ship EW=*  UAF-1 ESM, ''or'', UAT Mod 1\n* [[Seagnat]]\n* Type 182 towed torpedo decoy\n* [[SSTD|Surface Ship Torpedo Defence]]\n|Ship armament=\n*''Anti-air missiles:''\n**1 \u00d7 32-cell [[vertical launching system|GWS.26 VLS canisters]] for 32:\n**[[Sea Ceptor]] missiles (1\u201325+&nbsp;km)\n*''Anti-ship missiles:''\n**2 \u00d7 quad [[Harpoon (missile)|Harpoon]] launchers (8x missiles)\n*''Anti-submarine torpedoes:''\n**2 \u00d7 twin 12.75{{nbsp}}in (324{{nbsp}}mm) [[Sting Ray (torpedo)|Sting Ray torpedo]] tubes\n*''Guns:''\n**1 \u00d7 [[BAE Systems|BAE]] [[4.5 inch Mark 8 naval gun|4.5{{nbsp}}inch Mk{{nbsp}}8 naval gun]]\n**2 \u00d7 [[30mm DS30M Mark 2 Automated Small Calibre Gun|30{{nbsp}}mm DS30M Mk2 guns]], ''or'', 2 \u00d7 30{{nbsp}}mm DS30B guns\n**2 \u00d7 [[Minigun]]s\n**4 \u00d7 [[FN MAG|General-purpose machine gun]]\n|Ship armour=\n|Ship aircraft=*1 \u00d7 [[AgustaWestland AW159 Wildcat|Westland Wildcat HMA2]], armed with;\n* 2 \u00d7 anti submarine torpedoes\n*''or''\n*1 \u00d7 [[AgustaWestland AW101|Westland Merlin HM2]], armed with;\n* 4 \u00d7 anti submarine torpedoes\n|Ship aircraft facilities=* Flight deck\n* Enclosed [[hangar]]\n|Ship notes=\n}}\n|}\n\n'''HMS ''Richmond''''' is a [[Type 23 frigate|Type 23]] [[frigate]] of the [[Royal Navy]]. She was launched on 6 April 1993 by Lady Hill-Norton, wife of the late [[Peter Hill-Norton, Baron Hill-Norton|Admiral of the Fleet The Lord Hill-Norton]], and was the last warship to be built by [[Swan Hunter Shipbuilders]]. She sailed from the builders on the River Tyne in November 1994. She is named for the [[Duke of Richmond|Dukedom of Richmond]].\n\n==Operational history==\n===1995\u20132000===\n[[File:HMS Richmond.jpg|thumb|left|HMS ''Richmond'' in Portsmouth Naval Base]]\n[[File:US Navy 020612-N-9407M-518 British frigate HMS Richmond (F-239) launches an AGM-84A \"Harpoon\" missile.jpg|thumb|left|''Richmond'' launching an [[Boeing Harpoon|AGM-84 Harpoon]] missile]]\n[[File:US Navy 090326-N-4774B-125 The Royal Navy frigate HMS Richmond (F 239) patrols the waters surrounding the Al Basra Oil Terminal off the coast of Iraq while merchant vessels wait to take on oil.jpg|thumb|left|''Richmond'' patrolling near the [[Al Basrah Oil Terminal|Al Basra Oil Terminal]], Iraq]]\n''Richmond'' was first deployed in 1997 to the [[Far East]] as part of the 'Ocean Wave 97' Task Group. One of the most interesting visits she made was to the [[Russia]]n port of [[Vladivostok]], an important Russian naval base, where she became the first Royal Navy vessel to visit in over 100 years. Also that year ''Richmond'' escorted the [[royal yacht]] {{ship|HMY|Britannia}} on the ship's final leg of her final tour of the United Kingdom prior to her decommissioning.\n\nIn 1998 ''Richmond'' participated in two significant [[NATO]] naval exercises and arrived in [[New York City|New York]] where she was involved in the US Navy Fleet Week. In 1999 ''Richmond'' was dispatched to the South Atlantic as part of [[Atlantic Patrol Task (South)]] and underwent a major overhaul which concluded in 2000.\n\n===2001\u20132010===\nIn 2001 ''Richmond'' joined the NATO multi-national squadron [[Standing Naval Force Mediterranean]]. In 2002 she arrived in the Caribbean where she performed tasks including obligatory \"fly-the-flag\" duties to the [[Commonwealth of Nations|Commonwealth]] countries in the region as well as undergoing trials. In June 2002, two officers were killed when ''Richmond''{{'}}s [[HMS Richmond helicopter crash|Lynx helicopter crashed]] off the coast of Virginia.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk/2046318.stm |title=Navy investigators head for crash scene |date=15 June 2002 |website=[[BBC News]] |accessdate=31 August 2014}}</ref>\n\nIn 2003, under the command of Commander [[Wayne Keble]], she deployed to the [[Persian Gulf]] on [[Armilla Patrol]] where she relieved {{HMS|Cardiff|D108|6}}.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.royal-navy.mod.uk/server/show/conWebDoc.3706/changeNav/3533 |title=News and Events |website=Royal Navy |accessdate=4 March 2008}}{{dead link|date=June 2016|bot=medic}}{{cbignore|bot=medic}}</ref> She had arrived shortly before the [[2003 Iraq War]]. When hostilities began, ''Richmond'', HM ships {{HMS|Chatham|F87|2}}, {{HMS|Marlborough|F233|2}} and {{HMAS|Anzac|FFH 150|6}} of the [[Royal Australian Navy]] provided Naval Gunfire Support (NGS) during the [[Royal Marines]]' [[2003 invasion of Iraq#Opening attack|amphibious assault of the Al Faw Peninsula]], the first amphibious assault by the Marines since the [[Falklands War]] in 1982. ''Richmond'' remained in the region at the war's end and returned home in August.\n\nIn July 2004, under the command of Commander [[Mike McCartain]], ''Richmond'' deployed on [[Atlantic Patrol Task (North)]], which encompasses the Atlantic and [[Caribbean]] regions. Two of the ports she visited early in the deployment were [[Jamaica]] and [[Belize]]. In September ''Richmond'' came to the assistance of the [[Turks and Caicos Islands]] when they were struck by [[Hurricane Frances]].  Turks and Caicos suffered only minimal damage to buildings. ''Richmond'' then sailed to [[Cura\u00e7ao]], [[Netherlands Antilles]] where she resumed her maintenance period, which had been interrupted due to the hurricane, but remained on standby to provide assistance due to the imminent arrival of [[Hurricane Ivan]].\n\nHurricane Ivan eventually hit the region, causing significant damage and fatalities, particularly inflicting enormous damage and a number of fatalities to [[Grenada]], which included immense damage to the capital [[St. George's, Grenada|St. George's]]. ''Richmond'' and her accompanying [[Royal Fleet Auxiliary]] vessel {{ship|RFA|Wave Ruler|A390|2}} came to the assistance of the island. The extent of the damage in Grenada reached such levels that [[Keith Mitchell]], Prime Minister of Grenada, was forced to relocate to ''Richmond'' after his residence was destroyed by the hurricane. The Prime Minister effectively ran his country from ''Richmond'' for several hours.\n\nHer crew having performed vital assistance on land at Grenada, ''Richmond'' steamed at her top speed for Jamaica and the Cayman Islands to assist those territories in recovering from the ravages of Hurricane Ivan.\n\n''Richmond'' returned from her deployment in December 2004, and began a refit period at [[HMNB Portsmouth|HM Naval Base Portsmouth]] in mid-2005. The refit, undertaken by [[Fleet Support Limited]], was completed in late 2006 and ''Richmond'' was returned to the operational fleet in October 2006. With 44 major upgrades to her sensor and weapon systems, ''Richmond'' was at that time one of the most capable Type 23 frigates.<ref>{{cite magazine |url=http://www.fleet-support.co.uk/Docs/FirstBase/firstbase-winter2006.pdf |title=Fresh-faced ''Richmond'' re-dedicated to the Fleet |date=December 2006 |magazine=firstBASE |page=7 |publisher=[[HMNB Portsmouth]] |access-date=3 January 2007 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070809192438/http://www.fleet-support.co.uk/Docs/FirstBase/firstbase-winter2006.pdf |archive-date=9 August 2007}}</ref> From 5 to 12 July 2010 she anchored beside {{HMS|Belfast||6}} in London to foster the ship's relations with the [[London Borough of Richmond upon Thames|Borough of Richmond-upon-Thames]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.london-se1.co.uk/news/view/4659 |title=HMS ''Richmond'' arrives in the Pool of London |date=5 July 2010 |website=London SE1 |accessdate=5 April 2019}}</ref>\n\n===2011\u2013present===\n[[File:HMS Richmond at South Quay.jpg|thumb|left|HMS ''Richmond'' moored at South Quay in London in 2017]]\nIn 2011, she deployed to the Middle East and the Asia-Pacific region, the latter for upcoming [[Five Power Defence Arrangement]] exercises, specifically Exercise Bersama Shield 11.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.navynews.co.uk/news/1215-richmond-enjoys-some-happy-torque-in-the-far-east.aspx |title=''Richmond'' enjoys some happy torque in the Far East |newspaper=[[Navy News]]}} {{dead link|date=October 2016}}</ref> She assisted with anti-piracy operations with the EU Naval Force and was also a participant in the IMEX Asia 2011.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.mod.uk/DefenceInternet/DefenceNews/MilitaryOperations/HmsRichmondDeploysOnCounterpiracyMission.htm |author=Ministry of Defence |title=HMS ''Richmond'' deploys on counter-piracy mission  |date=5 January 2011 |website=[[Gov.uk]] |accessdate=5 April 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.cornwallcommunitynews.co.uk/2011/05/10/navy-take-on-pirates-real-ones/ |title=Navy Takes On Pirates (Real Ones) |date=10 May 2011 |website=Cornwall Community News |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110513134031/http://www.cornwallcommunitynews.co.uk/2011/05/10/navy-take-on-pirates-real-ones/ |archive-date=13 May 2011}}</ref> After Singapore, she rendered honours to the fallen of [[Force Z]] (see the [[Sinking of Prince of Wales and Repulse|Sinking of ''Prince of Wales'' and ''Repulse'']]).<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.navynews.co.uk/news/1203-richmond-honours-the-dead-of-force-z.aspx |title=''Richmond'' honours the dead of Force Z |newspaper=Navy News}} {{dead link|date=October 2016}}</ref>\n\nShe took part in exercise FRUKUS 2011 with ships from the [[United States Navy]] and [[Russian Navy]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://english.ruvr.ru/2011/06/01/51118143.html |title=Russian warship heads out for joint maneuvers |date=1 June 2011 |website=[[Sputnik (news agency)|Sputnik]] |access-date=1 June 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120906022428/http://english.ruvr.ru/2011/06/01/51118143.html |archive-date=6 September 2012 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nIn early August 2013, she deployed under the command of Commander Robert G. Pedre to be the ship for the Royal Navy's Atlantic Patrol South where she carried out Maritime Security Patrols in the [[Falkland Islands]]. HMS ''Richmond'' returned to the UK in February 2014. This deployment involved high profile defence engagement visits to five continents and resulted in the ship receiving Commander British Forces South Atlantic Islands Commendation for Distinguished Service.  Of note, during her seven months away ''Richmond'' conducted visits to five British Dependent Overseas Territories including [[Ascension Island]], [[St Helena]], the Falklands, [[South Georgia and the South Sandwich Islands|South Georgia]] and [[Tristan da Cunha]]. During this deployment ''Richmond'' became the first Royal Navy warship to transit the [[Panama Canal]] in its centenary year.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.royalnavy.mod.uk/News-and-Events/Latest-News/2013/August/05/130805-HMS-Richmond-deploys |title=HMS ''Richmond'' deploys on Atlantic patrol tasking |date=5 August 2013 |website=Royal Navy |accessdate=4 April 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn October 2015 ''Richmond'' was deployed to the Mediterranean to aid the EU's fight against people smugglers due to refugees fleeing civil war in Syria. She returned to her home port on 11 December 2015.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.royalnavy.mod.uk/news-and-latest-activity/news/2015/december/11/151211-hms-richmond-home |title=Drug-busting and life-saving HMS ''Richmond'' returns home from nine-month deployment |date=11 December 2015 |website=Royal Navy |accessdate=4 April 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn October 2016 ''Richmond'' and the [[destroyer]] {{HMS|Duncan|D37|6}} were dispatched by the [[Ministry of Defence (United Kingdom)|Ministry of Defence]] to intercept and \"man-mark\" a fleet of Russian Navy vessels, including their [[flagship]] {{ship|Russian aircraft carrier|Admiral Kuznetsov||2}} passing through the English Channel on their way to [[Syria]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-37725327 |title=Russian warships pass through English Channel |date=21 October 2016 |website=BBC News |accessdate=21 October 2016}}</ref>\n\nOn 6 January 2017, ''Richmond'' featured in Series 1, episode 9 of ''[[The Grand Tour (TV series)|The Grand Tour]]''. The ship and its weaponry star in a sequence where [[James May]] and [[Jeremy Clarkson]] commandeer its 4.5 inch Mark 8 naval gun to destroy an armoured vehicle manufactured by [[Richard Hammond]].\n\nIn June 2017, ''Richmond'' docked at [[Chatham, Kent|Chatham]] on the [[River Medway|Medway]] to mark 350 years since the [[Raid on the Medway]].\n\n''Richmond'' entered refit at Devonport in the late summer of 2017, in November it was announced that on completion of the work in 2018 she will not return to Portsmouth and will switch base port to Plymouth in an effort to concentrate the Type 23s fitted with anti-submarine equipment in the city.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.royalnavy.mod.uk/news-and-latest-activity/news/2017/november/24/171124-defence-secretary-announces-type-23-base-port-moves |title=Defence Secretary announces Type 23 base port moves |website=Royal Navy |date=24 November 2017 |accessdate=28 November 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Affiliations==\n* [[Charles Gordon-Lennox, 10th Duke of Richmond|His Grace, The Duke of Richmond and Gordon]]\n* [[Yorkshire Regiment|The Yorkshire Regiment (14th/15th, 19th and 33rd/76th Foot)]]\n* [[Worshipful Company of Basketmakers]]\n* [[Richmond, North Yorkshire|Town of Richmond]]\n* [[London Borough of Richmond upon Thames|Richmond upon Thames]]\n* [[London Nautical School]]\n\n== See also ==\n* [[HMS Richmond helicopter crash]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category}}\n*{{cite web |url=https://www.royalnavy.mod.uk/our-organisation/the-fighting-arms/surface-fleet/frigates/type-23/hms-richmond |title=HMS ''Richmond'' |website=Royal Navy}}\n\n{{Type 23 frigate}}\n{{Royal Navy ships}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Richmond}}\n[[Category:Active frigates of the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Ships built by Swan Hunter]]\n[[Category:Ships built on the River Tyne]]\n[[Category:1993 ships]]\n[[Category:Type 23 frigates of the Royal Navy]]\n", "name_user": "Hammersfan", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/HMS_Richmond_(F239)"}
{"title_page": "Giovanni Guida", "text_new": "[[File:Dipinto Apotheosis, grattage su tela.jpg|thumb|right|''Apotheosis'', grattage - oil painting on canvas, 2014]]\n'''Giovanni Guida''' (born 1992) is an Italian [[Art|artist]], [[Paint|painter]] and [[Illustration|illustrator]] from [[Cesa]], [[Caserta]]. His pictorial works are made with the [[Surrealism|surrealist]] technique of [[grattage]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Giovanni Guida ha dipinto il virus ispirandosi a Battiato |url=https://www.thewaymagazine.it/targets/giovanni-guida-ha-dipinto-il-virus-ispirandosi-a-battiato/ |website=The Way Magazine}}</ref>\n\nIn 2016, his painting \"Caesarius Diaconus\" (icon of [[Caesarius of Africa]]) was exhibited in many museums, cathedrals and basilicas in the world.<ref>Rossi Giovanni, L'icona di San Cesareo in \"tour\", in \"Vero\", anno XIII, n.46, 23 novembre 2017</ref><ref>Damiani Agostino, La nuova icona di S. Cesario gira il mondo, in \"Mio\", anno II, n.2, January 12, 2017</ref>\n\nIn 2020, his illustration of [[God]] who dematerializes the [[Covid-19]] molecule in order to end [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]], goes viral.<ref>{{cite web |title=Il messaggio evocativo dell\u2019arte ai tempi del Coronavirus |url=https://www.ilvaloreitaliano.it/il-messaggio-evocativo-dellarte-ai-tempi-del-coronavirus/ |website=Valore Italiano}}</ref>\n\n==Biography==\nIn 2015, he graduated with honors in [[Painting]] from the [[Academy of Fine Arts]] in [[Naples]]. \n\nHis painting is based on the dynamic value of the '[[sign]]', with soft and sinuous lines that intertwine and intersect each other. He deepens his research on [[color]] and [[light]], moving towards an [[abstract art]], through the techniques of [[grattage]] and [[Frottage (art)|frottage]]. For this method of work, he makes use of new tools, experimenting with common utensils and everyday objects, such as sponges, steel brushes, and small metal blocks.\n[[File:E guarirai da tutte le malattie ed io, avr\u00f2 cura di te, (Dio blocca il Coronavirus (COVID-19) sull'Italia), china su graphia, Giovanni Guida 2020.jpg|thumb|right| Illustration ''God fights the [[Coronavirus]] on the world'', grattage on graphia, 2020]]\n\nIn 2015 his painting \"Lux: [[Giuseppe Diana]]\" was published on \"[[L'Osservatore Romano]]\" - the daily newspaper of [[Vatican City State]].<ref>La luce vince l'ombra, in \"L'Osservatore Romano\", August 29, 2015</ref>\n\nIn 2018, his painting \"Apotheosis\" was published on the cover of the catalog of the [[Public Library of Valencia]] for the Festival of Philosophy and Literature ''Avivament''.<ref>\"Literatura i Filosofia. Festival de Filosofia a Val\u00e8ncia (6-9 juny 2018) AVIVAMENT\", Val\u00e8ncia Bibliotecas P\u00fablicas, 2018</ref> \n\nIn 2019, \"Diarchia: the embrace between [[Matteo Salvini]] and [[Luigi Di Maio]]\" was published in the newspapers ''[[la Repubblica]]''<ref>{{cite web |title=Salvini e Di Maio tetrarchi Guida: \" In quell'abbraccio il patto di convenienza\" |url=https://ricerca.repubblica.it/repubblica/archivio/repubblica/2019/05/08/salvini-e-di-maio-tetrarchi-guida--in-quellabbraccio-convenienzaNapoli17.html |website=La Repubblica}}</ref> and ''[[Il Fatto Quotidiano]].<ref>Diarchia tra i gialloverdi, in \"Il Fatto Quotidiano\", May 3, 2019</ref>'' \n\nOn 5 February 2020 the Italian newspaper ''[[Avvenire]]'' publishes his illustration of \"[[Agatha of Sicily]]\".<ref>Agata. La forza della purezza trionfa sulla violenza e diventa profezia che cambia la storia, in \"Avvenire\", February 5, 2020</ref>\n\nOn 20 February 2020 the Italian newspaper ''[[Il Corriere della Sera]]''<ref>{{cite web |title=Diodato, live alla Feltrinelli |url=https://corrieredelmezzogiorno.corriere.it/napoli/spettacoli/20_febbraio_20/diodato-live-feltrinelli-a1e2b6a8-53d7-11ea-9d90-7863bdf03aae.shtml |website=Corriere della Sera}}</ref> publishes his illustration \"Fai rumore\", a portrait of the singer-songwriter [[Diodato]], winner of the [[Sanremo Music Festival 2020|70th edition]] of [[Sanremo Music Festival]]; the image goes viral.<ref>{{cite web |title=Diodato nella sua Taranto: premiato con attestato benemerenza dal Comune. L'artista Giovanni Guida gli ha dedicato un disegno |url=https://www.lagazzettadelmezzogiorno.it/news/taranto/1207164/diodato-nella-sua-taranto-l-omaggio-di-un-artista-e-virale.html |website=La Gazzetta del Mezzogiorno}}</ref> \n\nIn March 2020, his illustration \"And you will recover from all diseases .. and I will take care of you\" (God fights the [[Coronavirus]] - [[Covid-19]] - on the world) is published in newspapers, on the ''[[Treccani]]'' website<ref>{{cite web |title=L\u2019Europa e la pandemia: parole di presidenti a confronto |url=http://www.treccani.it/magazine/lingua_italiana/articoli/parole/parole_nel_turbine_2.html |website=Treccani}}</ref>, and in the newspaper ''[[Leggo]]''.<ref>{{cite web |title=Coronavirus, l'opera dell'artista Giovanni Guida donata a Leggo: \"E guarirai da tutte le malattie...\" |url=https://www.leggo.it/arte/coronavirus_opera_artista_giovanni_guida_donata_leggo_guarirai_da_tutte_le_malattie-5138767.html |website=Leggo}}</ref>\n\n==Exhibitions==\n[[File:Reliquia San Cesario nel Museo Frederic Mares di Barcellona.jpg|thumb|right|[[Barcelona]], [[Museu Frederic Mar\u00e8s]]: the director dr. Josep Maria Trull\u00e9n next to the icon \"Caesarius Diaconus\"]]\n*\"Caesarius Diaconus\", [[Kunstgewerbemuseum Berlin|Kunstgewerbemuseum]] in [[Berlin]] (by the director Dr. Sabine Th\u00fcmmler); the [[Museu Frederic Mar\u00e8s]] in [[Barcelona]] (by the director Dr. Josep Maria Trull\u00e9n); the Museum of S\u00e3o Roque in [[Lisbon]]; the Terra Sancta Museum in [[Jerusalem]]; the Slovak National Museum - Historical Museum of [[Bratislava]]; the Stiftsmuseum of [[Aschaffenburg]]; Mus\u00e9e Europ\u00e9en de la Visitation, [[Moulins, Allier|Moulins]]; the Diocesan Museum of [[Monreale]]; the Museums of the Cathedral of [[Modena]]; and the Museum of San Fedele in [[Milan]]; [[St. Joseph Cathedral in Buffalo]] (by bishop [[Richard Joseph Malone]]); Saint Anthony's Chapel in [[Pittsburgh]]; [[St. Raphael's Cathedral (Dubuque, Iowa)|St. Raphael's Cathedral in Dubuque]]; [[Manila Cathedral]] (by the cardinal [[Luis Antonio Tagle]]); [[Essen Cathedral]]; [[St. Maria im Kapitol|Basilica St. Maria im Kapitol]] in [[Cologne]]; Basilica of [[Santa Croce in Gerusalemme]] in [[Rome]]; [[Sancta Sanctorum]] of Rome; [[Naples Cathedral]]; and [[Basilica of San Frediano]] in [[Lucca]]), 2016.<ref>Sergio Luciano, ''Il viaggio nel mondo dell'icona di San Cesario di Terracina\", in \"Economy Mag\", May 3, 2018</ref>\n*\"Diarchia: the embrace between [[Matteo Salvini]] and [[Luigi Di Maio]]\", Museum PAN, Naples, 1\u201319 May 2019.<ref>{{cite web |title=Diarchia, fraternitas tra Salvini e Di Maio: l'opera di Giovanni Guida |url=https://www.affaritaliani.it/culturaspettacoli/diarchia-fraternitas-tra-salvini-di-maio-607779.html |website=Affari Italiani}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Dal bel canto alla notte dei musei: ecco tutti gli eventi del weekend a Napoli |url=https://www.ilmattino.it/napolismart/in_evidenza/weekend_eventi_napoli_18_19_maggio-4498182.html |website=Il Mattino}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Commons category}}\n{{Reflist}}\n\n[[Category:1992 births]]\n[[Category:Italian male painters]]\n[[Category:21st-century Italian painters]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n", "text_old": "[[File:Dipinto Apotheosis, grattage su tela.jpg|thumb|right|''Apotheosis'', grattage - oil painting on canvas, 2014]]\n'''Giovanni Guida''' (born 1992) is an Italian [[Art|artist]], [[Paint|painter]] and [[Illustration|illustrator]] from [[Cesa]], [[Caserta]]. His pictorial works are made with the [[Surrealism|surrealist]] technique of [[grattage]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Giovanni Guida ha dipinto il virus ispirandosi a Battiato |url=https://www.thewaymagazine.it/targets/giovanni-guida-ha-dipinto-il-virus-ispirandosi-a-battiato/ |website=The Way Magazine}}</ref>\n\nIn 2016, his painting \"Caesarius Diaconus\" (icon of [[Caesarius of Africa]]) was exhibited in many museums, cathedrals and basilicas in the world.<ref>Rossi Giovanni, L'icona di San Cesareo in \"tour\", in \"Vero\", anno XIII, n.46, 23 novembre 2017</ref><ref>Damiani Agostino, La nuova icona di S. Cesario gira il mondo, in \"Mio\", anno II, n.2, January 12, 2017</ref>\n\nIn 2020, his illustration of [[God]] who dematerializes the [[Covid-19]] molecule in order to end [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]], goes viral.<ref>{{cite web |title=Il messaggio evocativo dell\u2019arte ai tempi del Coronavirus |url=https://www.ilvaloreitaliano.it/il-messaggio-evocativo-dellarte-ai-tempi-del-coronavirus/ |website=Valore Italiano}}</ref>\n\n==Biography==\nIn 2015, he graduated with honors in [[Painting]] from the [[Academy of Fine Arts]] in [[Naples]]. \n\nHis painting is based on the dynamic value of the '[[sign]]', with soft and sinuous lines that intertwine and intersect each other. He deepens his research on [[color]] and [[light]], moving towards an [[abstract art]], through the techniques of [[grattage]] and [[Frottage (art)|frottage]]. For this method of work, he makes use of new tools, experimenting with common utensils and everyday objects, such as sponges, steel brushes, and small metal blocks.\n[[File:E guarirai da tutte le malattie ed io, avr\u00f2 cura di te, (Dio blocca il Coronavirus (COVID-19) sull'Italia), china su graphia, Giovanni Guida 2020.jpg|thumb|right| Illustration ''God fights the [[Coronavirus]] on the world'', grattage on graphia, 2020]]\n\nIn 2015 his painting \"Lux: [[Giuseppe Diana]]\" was published on \"[[L'Osservatore Romano]]\" - the daily newspaper of [[Vatican City State]].<ref>La luce vince l'ombra, in \"L'Osservatore Romano\", August 29, 2015</ref>\n\nIn 2018, his painting \"Apotheosis\" was published on the cover of the catalog of the [[Public Library of Valencia]] for the Festival of Philosophy and Literature ''Avivament''.<ref>\"Literatura i Filosofia. Festival de Filosofia a Val\u00e8ncia (6-9 juny 2018) AVIVAMENT\", Val\u00e8ncia Bibliotecas P\u00fablicas, 2018</ref> \n\nIn 2019, \"Diarchia: the embrace between [[Matteo Salvini]] and [[Luigi Di Maio]]\" was published in the newspapers ''[[la Repubblica]]''<ref>{{cite web |title=Salvini e Di Maio tetrarchi Guida: \" In quell'abbraccio il patto di convenienza\" |url=https://ricerca.repubblica.it/repubblica/archivio/repubblica/2019/05/08/salvini-e-di-maio-tetrarchi-guida--in-quellabbraccio-convenienzaNapoli17.html |website=La Repubblica}}</ref> and ''[[Il Fatto Quotidiano]].<ref>Diarchia tra i gialloverdi, in \"Il Fatto Quotidiano\", May 3, 2019</ref>'' \n\nOn 5 February 2020 the Italian newspaper ''[[Avvenire]]'' publishes his illustration of \"[[Agatha of Sicily]]\".<ref>Agata. La forza della purezza trionfa sulla violenza e diventa profezia che cambia la storia, in \"Avvenire\", February 5, 2020</ref>\n\nOn 20 February 2020 the Italian newspaper ''[[Il Corriere della Sera]]''<ref>{{cite web |title=Diodato, live alla Feltrinelli |url=https://corrieredelmezzogiorno.corriere.it/napoli/spettacoli/20_febbraio_20/diodato-live-feltrinelli-a1e2b6a8-53d7-11ea-9d90-7863bdf03aae.shtml |website=Corriere della Sera}}</ref> publishes his illustration \"Fai rumore\", a portrait of the singer-songwriter [[Diodato]], winner of the the [[Sanremo Music Festival 2020|70th edition]] of [[Sanremo Music Festival]]; the image goes viral.<ref>{{cite web |title=Diodato nella sua Taranto: premiato con attestato benemerenza dal Comune. L'artista Giovanni Guida gli ha dedicato un disegno |url=https://www.lagazzettadelmezzogiorno.it/news/taranto/1207164/diodato-nella-sua-taranto-l-omaggio-di-un-artista-e-virale.html |website=La Gazzetta del Mezzogiorno}}</ref> \n\nIn March 2020, his illustration \"And you will recover from all diseases .. and I will take care of you\" (God fights the [[Coronavirus]] - [[Covid-19]] - on the world) is published in newspapers, on the ''[[Treccani]]'' website<ref>{{cite web |title=L\u2019Europa e la pandemia: parole di presidenti a confronto |url=http://www.treccani.it/magazine/lingua_italiana/articoli/parole/parole_nel_turbine_2.html |website=Treccani}}</ref>, and in the newspaper ''[[Leggo]]''.<ref>{{cite web |title=Coronavirus, l'opera dell'artista Giovanni Guida donata a Leggo: \"E guarirai da tutte le malattie...\" |url=https://www.leggo.it/arte/coronavirus_opera_artista_giovanni_guida_donata_leggo_guarirai_da_tutte_le_malattie-5138767.html |website=Leggo}}</ref>\n\n==Exhibitions==\n[[File:Reliquia San Cesario nel Museo Frederic Mares di Barcellona.jpg|thumb|right|[[Barcelona]], [[Museu Frederic Mar\u00e8s]]: the director dr. Josep Maria Trull\u00e9n next to the icon \"Caesarius Diaconus\"]]\n*\"Caesarius Diaconus\", [[Kunstgewerbemuseum Berlin|Kunstgewerbemuseum]] in [[Berlin]] (by the director Dr. Sabine Th\u00fcmmler); the [[Museu Frederic Mar\u00e8s]] in [[Barcelona]] (by the director Dr. Josep Maria Trull\u00e9n); the Museum of S\u00e3o Roque in [[Lisbon]]; the Terra Sancta Museum in [[Jerusalem]]; the Slovak National Museum - Historical Museum of [[Bratislava]]; the Stiftsmuseum of [[Aschaffenburg]]; Mus\u00e9e Europ\u00e9en de la Visitation, [[Moulins, Allier|Moulins]]; the Diocesan Museum of [[Monreale]]; the Museums of the Cathedral of [[Modena]]; and the Museum of San Fedele in [[Milan]]; [[St. Joseph Cathedral in Buffalo]] (by bishop [[Richard Joseph Malone]]); Saint Anthony's Chapel in [[Pittsburgh]]; [[St. Raphael's Cathedral (Dubuque, Iowa)|St. Raphael's Cathedral in Dubuque]]; [[Manila Cathedral]] (by the cardinal [[Luis Antonio Tagle]]); [[Essen Cathedral]]; [[St. Maria im Kapitol|Basilica St. Maria im Kapitol]] in [[Cologne]]; Basilica of [[Santa Croce in Gerusalemme]] in [[Rome]]; [[Sancta Sanctorum]] of Rome; [[Naples Cathedral]]; and [[Basilica of San Frediano]] in [[Lucca]]), 2016.<ref>Sergio Luciano, ''Il viaggio nel mondo dell'icona di San Cesario di Terracina\", in \"Economy Mag\", May 3, 2018</ref>\n*\"Diarchia: the embrace between [[Matteo Salvini]] and [[Luigi Di Maio]]\", Museum PAN, Naples, 1\u201319 May 2019.<ref>{{cite web |title=Diarchia, fraternitas tra Salvini e Di Maio: l'opera di Giovanni Guida |url=https://www.affaritaliani.it/culturaspettacoli/diarchia-fraternitas-tra-salvini-di-maio-607779.html |website=Affari Italiani}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Dal bel canto alla notte dei musei: ecco tutti gli eventi del weekend a Napoli |url=https://www.ilmattino.it/napolismart/in_evidenza/weekend_eventi_napoli_18_19_maggio-4498182.html |website=Il Mattino}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Commons category}}\n{{Reflist}}\n\n[[Category:1992 births]]\n[[Category:Italian male painters]]\n[[Category:21st-century Italian painters]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n", "name_user": "Arjayay", "label": "safe", "comment": "Duplicate word removed", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Giovanni_Guida"}
